{{EngvarB|date=March 2019}} {{Use British English|date=February 2017}} {{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}} {{Infobox football biography | name = Lewis Dunk | image = BHA v FC Nantes pre season 03 08 2018-322 (42044181000) (cropped).jpg | image_size = 200 | caption = Dunk playing for [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] in 2018 | fullname = Lewis Carl Dunk<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/612828 |title=Updated squads for 2017/18 Premier League confirmed |publisher=Premier League |date=2 February 2018 |accessdate=10 February 2018}}</ref> | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1991|11|21|df=y}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/players/8163/Lewis-Dunk/overview |title=Lewis Dunk: Overview |publisher=Premier League |accessdate=17 March 2019}}</ref> | birth_place = [[Brighton]], England | height = {{convert|1.92|m|order=flip}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/teams/first-team/defender/lewis-dunk/ |title=Lewis Dunk |publisher=Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. |accessdate=17 March 2019}}</ref> | currentclub = [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] | clubnumber = 5 | position = [[Centre back]] | youthyears1 = {{0|0000}}–2010 | youthclubs1 = [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] | years1 = 2010– | clubs1 = [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] | caps1 = 235 | goals1 = 13 | years2 = 2013 | clubs2 = → [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]] (loan) | caps2 = 2 | goals2 = 0 | nationalyears1 = 2018– | nationalteam1 = [[England national football team|England]] | nationalcaps1 = 1 | nationalgoals1 = 0 | club-update = 14:30, 9 March 2019 (UTC) | nationalteam-update = 17:20, 19 January 2019 (UTC) }} '''Lewis Carl Dunk''' (born 21 November 1991) is an English professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[centre back]] for {{English football updater|Brigh&HA}} club [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] and the [[England national football team|England national team]].
==Early life== Dunk was born in [[Brighton]], East Sussex.<ref>{{cite book |editor-first=Barry J. |editor-last=Hugman |title=The PFA Footballers' Who's Who 2010–11 |year=2010 |publisher=Mainstream Publishing |location=Edinburgh |isbn=978-1-84596-601-0 |page=129}}</ref> He is the son of former Sussex non-league player Mark Dunk.<ref name="Dunk debut">{{cite news |url=http://www.theargus.co.uk/sport/8132511.Dunk_debut_for_Albion/ |title=Dunk debut for Albion |newspaper=The Argus |location=Brighton |date=1 May 2010 |accessdate=1 July 2010}}</ref>
==Club career== ===Brighton & Hove Albion=== ====Early career==== [[File:Lewis Dunk.jpg|thumb|upright|Dunk playing for [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] in 2011]]
On 30 April 2010, Dunk signed a two-year professional contract with [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] following impressive performances captaining the club's youth team.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theargus.co.uk/sport/8129342.Seagulls_award_pro_deals_to_hot_prospects/ |title=Seagulls award pro deals to hot prospects |newspaper=The Argus |location=Brighton |date=30 April 2010 |accessdate=1 July 2010}}</ref> The following day, Dunk made his first professional appearance starting in the 0–0 draw at [[Milton Keynes Dons F.C.|Milton Keynes Dons]].<ref name="Dunk debut"/>
On 31 January 2011, Dunk signed a one-year extension on his contract keeping him at the club until the summer of 2013.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/brighton/9382827.stm |title=Brighton defender signs new deal |publisher=BBC Sport |date=31 January 2011 |accessdate=31 January 2011}}</ref> Dunk made eight appearances in the [[2010–11 Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. season|2010–11 season]]<ref name=sb1011/> as Brighton gained promotion to the [[EFL Championship|Championship]] as [[EFL League One|League One]] champions.<ref>{{cite web |title=League One: 2010/11: Latest table |url=http://www.soccerbase.com/tournaments/tournament.sd?tourn_id=6 |website=Soccerbase |publisher=Centurycomm |accessdate=22 November 2017}}</ref>
With fellow defenders [[Tommy Elphick]] and [[Adam El-Abd]] sidelined by injury, Dunk started the [[2011–12 Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. season|2011–12 season]] alongside captain [[Gordon Greer]], playing in Brighton's first ever match at [[Falmer Stadium]] versus [[Doncaster Rovers F.C.|Doncaster Rovers]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Brighton & Hove Albion 2–1 Doncaster Rovers |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/brighton-vs-doncaster/238257 |publisher=Sky Sports |date=6 August 2011 |accessdate=30 December 2018}}</ref>
====Bristol City (loan)==== On 4 October 2013, Dunk joined League One club [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]] on a one-month loan deal, to gain some first-team football.<ref>{{cite web |first=Adam |last=Baker |title=City deal in Dunk |url=http://www.bcfc.co.uk/news/article/20131004-lewisdunk-1094148.aspx |publisher=Bristol City F.C. |date=4 October 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170301010419/http://www.bcfc.co.uk/news/article/20131004-lewisdunk-1094148.aspx |archivedate=1 March 2017 |deadurl=yes}}</ref> He made his debut for the club in a 2–1 away defeat to [[Wycombe Wanderers F.C.|Wycombe Wanderers]] on 8 October 2013, in the [[EFL Trophy]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Wycombe Wanderers 2–1 Bristol City |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/wycombe-vs-bristol-c/report/303217 |publisher=Sky Sports |date=8 October 2013 |accessdate=30 December 2018}}</ref>
====Return to Brighton & Hove Albion==== On 25 July 2014, Dunk signed a new four-year contract with [[Brighton & Hove Albion|Brighton]], which kept him at the club until the end of the [[2017–18 Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. season|2017–18]] season.<ref>{{cite web |first=Tim |last=Dudding |title=New deal for Dunk |url=https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/2014/july/new-deal-for-dunk/ |publisher=Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. |date=25 July 2014 |accessdate=22 November 2017}}</ref> He scored his first goal for Brighton in the club's first game of the [[2014–15 Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. season|2014–15]] season, a 2–0 win over [[Cheltenham Town F.C.|Cheltenham Town]] in the [[EFL Cup]], in a game that marked new boss [[Sami Hyypiä]]'s first win at the club.<ref>{{cite web |title=Brighton & Hove Albion 2–0 Cheltenham Town |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/28652372 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=13 August 2014 |accessdate=30 December 2018}}</ref>
Dunk formed a partnership at [[centre back]] with new Brighton signing [[Shane Duffy]] in the [[2016–17 Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. season|2016–17]] season, with the club conceding a joint-league best of 40 goals for the season, in which Brighton were promoted to the [[Premier League]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Championship Table 2016/17 Season |url=https://www.skysports.com/championship-table/2016 |publisher=Sky Sports |date=30 May 2017 |accessdate=30 December 2018}}</ref>
Dunk played the full 90 minutes, and scored an own goal, in Brighton's first ever [[Premier League]] match, a 0–2 home defeat to [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Brighton & Hove Albion 0–2 Manchester City |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40835422 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=12 August 2017 |accessdate=30 December 2018}}</ref> On 24 February 2018, Dunk scored his fourth own goal of the season in a 4–1 home win over [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Brighton & Hove Albion 4–1 Swansea City |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43094255 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=24 February 2018 |accessdate=30 December 2018}}</ref> which brought him level with [[Martin Škrtel]] at the top of the list of most own goals in a season in the [[Premier League]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Unlucky Dunk equals record for own goals |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/628553 |publisher=Premier League |date=26 February 2018 |accessdate=30 December 2018}}</ref> He scored his first [[Premier League]] goal in a 2–1 victory over [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] on 4 March 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=Brighton & Hove Albion 2–1 Arsenal |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43186393/ |publisher=BBC Sport |date=4 March 2018 |accessdate=30 December 2018}}</ref> Dunk played in every game in Brighton's debut season in the [[Premier League]], as the club finished in 15th place and amassed 40 points.<ref name=sb1718/>
On 5 October 2018, Dunk, alongside [[centre back]] partner [[Shane Duffy]], signed a new contract with Brighton, with the pair signing five-year contracts that extended their stay at the club until June 2023.<ref>{{cite web |title=New deals for Dunk and Duffy |url=https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/2018/october/new-deals-for-dunk-and-duffy/ |publisher=Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. |date=5 October 2018 |accessdate=30 December 2018}}</ref>
==International career== Dunk received a call-up to the [[England national under-21 football team|England under-21]] squad ahead of their [[2013 UEFA European Under-21 Championship qualification Group 8|European Championship qualifiers]] against [[Iceland national under-21 football team|Iceland]] and [[Belgium national under-21 football team|Belgium]] in November 2011,<ref>{{cite web |title=Squad named for Iceland and Belgium games |url=http://www.thefa.com/England/mens-under-21s/News/match-centre/2011/England-v-Iceland-Euro-2013/Match-Previews/squad-named-england-u21s-colchester/ |publisher=The Football Association |date=2 November 2011 |accessdate=2 November 2011}}</ref> but did not take the field in either match. In October 2018, he was called up to replace the injured [[James Tarkowski]] in the [[England national football team|senior England squad]] for matches against [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]] and [[Spain national football team|Spain]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thefa.com/news/2018/oct/07/england-squad-update-071018 |title=Brighton defender Lewis Dunk to join England squad for Croatia and Spain trip |publisher=The Football Association |date=7 October 2018 |accessdate=9 October 2018}}</ref> He made his debut on 15 November when starting England's 3–0 win over the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] at [[Wembley Stadium]] in a [[Exhibition game#Association football|friendly]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45174412 |title=England 3–0 USA |first=Phil |last=McNulty |publisher=BBC Sport |date=15 November 2018 |accessdate=15 November 2018}}</ref>
